<article class="post">
    <h2>Understanding Simple Harmonic Motion (SHM)</h2>
    <p class="date">Published on May 26, 2025</p>
    <p class="excerpt">
        Simple Harmonic Motion (SHM) is a type of periodic motion where the restoring force is directly proportional to the displacement and acts in the direction opposite to that of displacement.
    </p>
    
    <p>
        A classic example of SHM is a **mass on a spring**. The force obeys Hooke's Law:
    </p>
    
    <p style="text-align: center;">
        <em>F = -kx</em>
    </p>
    
    <p>
        where:
        <ul>
            <li><strong>F</strong> is the restoring force</li>
            <li><strong>k</strong> is the spring constant</li>
            <li><strong>x</strong> is the displacement from equilibrium</li>
        </ul>
    </p>

    <p>
        The motion can be described by the equation:
    </p>
    
    <p style="text-align: center;">
        <em>x(t) = A cos(ωt + φ)</em>
    </p>

    <p>
        where:
        <ul>
            <li><strong>A</strong> is the amplitude</li>
            <li><strong>ω</strong> is the angular frequency, ω = √(k/m)</li>
            <li><strong>φ</strong> is the phase constant</li>
        </ul>
    </p>

    <figure>
        <img src="assets/shm_diagram.png" alt="Simple Harmonic Motion Diagram" style="max-width:100%;">
        <figcaption>Figure: Diagram of a mass on a spring showing SHM.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
        SHM is foundational in understanding **oscillations**, **waves**, and **quantum mechanics**. It also appears in pendulums, AC circuits, and molecular vibrations.
    </p>
</article>
